# Skill Authoring Rules

When asked to create or edit an agent skill file (SKILL.md), follow these rules strictly.

---

## Purpose of a Skill

A skill is a markdown file loaded into an agent's context to teach it how to accomplish a specific, bounded task. It is **not** developer documentation — it is runtime instructions for a model. Every sentence should either help the agent decide what to do or tell it how to do it.

---

## Structure

Every skill must start with YAML frontmatter, followed by these sections in order:

```markdown
---
name: bc-<domain>-<verb>-<resource>  # e.g. bc-admissions-create-cohort, bc-billing-cancel-plan
description: <one sentence: when to use AND when not to use>
requires:
  - <other-skill-name>  # omit if no dependencies
---

# Skill: <Short Action-Oriented Title>

## When to Use
## Concepts (optional)
## Workflow
## Endpoints
## Edge Cases
## Checklist
```

The frontmatter `description` is read by the skill registry to decide whether to load this file at all. It must be a single sentence that includes at least one negative case ("do NOT use for..."). The `## When to Use` section inside the body gives the model finer-grained guidance once loaded. Both are required — they serve different audiences.

---

## Section Rules

### When to Use
- Always include this section, even if the trigger seems obvious.
- State clearly when to use AND when NOT to use this skill.
- Include at least one negative example to prevent over-triggering.
- Keep it to 5 lines or fewer.

### Concepts (optional)
- Only include if domain terms need defining for the agent to reason correctly.
- Skip if the workflow section is self-explanatory.
- No implementation internals (no model paths, class names, or ORM details).

### Workflow
- This is the most important section.
- Every step must be numbered and sequential.
- If a step depends on output from a previous step, say so explicitly (e.g. "use the `id` returned in Step 1").
- If order matters, explain WHY briefly — don't assume the agent will infer it.
- If a prerequisite skill or external doc is required, name it explicitly and explain what to do if it's unavailable.

### Endpoints
- Document only the endpoints this skill actually uses.
- For each endpoint include: method, path, required headers, required body fields, and what the response returns that matters.
- Do not document endpoints that belong in a different skill.

### Edge Cases
- List failure modes the agent should handle gracefully.
- For each edge case: what the agent will observe, and what it should do.
- Do not leave the agent in a silent dead end (e.g. "if X returns empty, do Y, not nothing").

### Checklist
- End every skill with a numbered checklist the agent can use to self-verify completion.
- Each item should be a concrete, observable action — not a vague principle.

---

## Naming Convention

Skill names must follow the pattern `bc-<domain>-<verb>-<resource>` in kebab-case (lowercase, hyphens only — no underscores, no uppercase). The spec does not allow underscores. The "bc" at the beginning of the name stands for BreateCode.

- **domain**: the API or product area — one word (e.g. `admissions`, `billing`, `certificates`, `syllabus`)
- **verb**: the action being performed (e.g. `create`, `enroll`, `cancel`, `list`, `issue`)
- **resource**: the thing being acted on (e.g. `cohort`, `student`, `plan`, `certificate`)

**Good names:**
```
bc-admissions-create-cohort
bc-admissions-enroll-student
bc-admissions-list-cohorts
bc-billing-create-plan
bc-billing-cancel-plan
bc-certificates-issue-certificate
bc-syllabus-create-version
```

**Bad names — do not use:**
```
cohort-creator          # no domain prefix, noun-based
new-cohort-flow         # vague, not action-resource pattern
bc-admissions-createCohort # camelCase not allowed
bc-admissions-create_cohort # underscores not allowed
createCohort            # no domain, camelCase
```

The domain prefix is critical at scale — it groups related skills alphabetically and makes the skill index scannable. Never omit it, even for skills that seem obvious. Before naming a new skill, check existing skill names to avoid near-duplicates that would confuse the registry.

---

## Scope Rules

### One skill = one user-facing task
A skill should cover exactly one task a user would ask for by name. If you find yourself writing "this skill also covers...", that's a second skill.

**Signs a skill needs to be split:**
- It has more than one H2 workflow section
- It covers both read and write operations on the same resource
- It includes both API-facing and ops/admin-facing instructions (e.g. management commands)

### What does NOT belong in a skill
- Internal code references: model paths, class names, receiver functions, ORM queries
- Management commands or shell scripts unless the skill is explicitly for ops tasks
- Background implementation context ("this works because...")
- Links to related files the agent cannot load or act on
- **References to Django Admin or any non-API tool.** Skills are API-only. Do not mention Admin, back-office UIs, or where to configure things outside the API. If an operation is not exposed by the API, say so without naming Admin (e.g. "the API does not expose X" or "must be configured first").

---

## Tone and Style

- Write for a model, not a developer. Assume zero context outside what's in the file.
- Use imperative instructions: "Call X", "Save the returned id", "If Y is empty, do Z".
- Avoid passive voice and vague language ("should", "might", "can be used to").
- JSON examples must use realistic placeholder values, not abstract placeholders like `<string>`.
- Every example must include all required fields — no incomplete snippets.

---

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

| Anti-pattern | Why it's a problem |
|---|---|
| Referencing external docs without fallback instructions | Agent silently fails if the doc isn't loaded |
| Mixing API tasks with admin/ops tasks | Breaks agents that only have API access |
| Including code internals (model paths, class names) | Adds noise, agent can't act on them |
| Vague "when to use" in the opening paragraph | Skill may be applied in wrong contexts |
| No negative examples in "When to Use" | Skill over-triggers on loosely related requests |
| Silent failure paths in edge cases | Agent gets stuck without knowing what to do |
| Steps that assume implicit ordering | Agent may call endpoints out of order |
| Skill name without domain prefix (e.g. `create-cohort`) | Skills don't group, registry becomes unscannable at scale |
| Underscores or camelCase in skill name | Violates the agentskills.io spec, may break validation |
| Near-duplicate names (e.g. `bc-admissions-create-cohort` and `bc-admissions-cohort-create`) | Registry picks wrong skill, inconsistent behavior |
| Mentioning Django Admin or directing users to configure things outside the API | Skills must describe only API behavior; do not reference Admin or other non-API tools |
